comment: Read about narcissistic abuse. Amber Heard displays most of the traits of someone with narcissistic personality disorder. It‚Äôs causes a psychological type of abuse that affects over 85 million people every year. I am by no means a celebrity, but I am a public figure. My career as an actor was used against me. These people go for the jugular. They lie and produce smear campaigns. And there are not usually bruises or broken bones on the actual victim. Law enforcement lacks the insight and awareness to discern the difference between the victim and the abuser because the abuser generally gets to the police first. Calling in false situations and pursuing malicious prosecution. I knew months ago that Heard was a narcissist just off of a few behaviors she had displayed. I know that Johnny Depp will pull through. She messed with Hollywood‚Äôs respected sweetheart and she will run herself and her career right into the ground, just like my ex, the future mental health therapist did. The truth will always surface. It is imperative that we prosecute psychological abusers. We have done that for physical and sexual abuse. But it‚Äôs time now to change the trajectory of outcomes for victims of psychological abuse. This video has inspired me and validated me in so many ways. I am pursuing my own lawsuit against my former partner. This disorder is too dangerous to ignore. It Perpetuates the trauma and abuse cycle. We need psychological abuse reform so we don‚Äôt have to resort to simply slander and libel and emotional distress cases that demand the victim prove damages. Rather, oh that should be proven was that a crime was committed.

Bipolar Disorder, like Kanye West has talked about, has a couple of categories but basically when a person experiences depression over a period of time and at least 1 manic episode (manic meaning period of feeling high or overly happy, extreme irritability, talking very fast, jumping from one topic to another, racing thoughts, easily distracted, increasing new projects or activities to where it interferes with day to day necessary life activities such as work, sleeping very little like when you‚Äôve had too much caffeine or other ‚Äústimulants‚Äù, high sex drive that‚Äôs clearly not that person‚Äôs usual behavior pattern. She should, and may have already, had a full Psychiatric evaluation, and she should have a Physician and a therapist working with her as she likely needs medicated for Bipolar Disorder and therapy for a possible personality disorder though most people refuse, and therapy is life-long and personality disorders are rarely, if ever, ‚Äúcured‚Äù. comment:
I listened to as many of those recordings as I could, and I recognized her.  Not her specifically, of course, but her manner of speaking.. the constant manipulation attempts to spin everything in her favor.  I used to have a lady like that... sexy as hell, crazy as hell, gas-lighter from hell.

One thing she used to do all of the time was take offense at some innocuous comment someone made, be it myself or some random third person, that clearly wasn't meant in any negative light.  If I, in an attempt to avoid the inevitable verbal explosion and resulting scene, attempted to clarify, and say something about "Well, what I think she may have meant was.. blah blah... I don't think she meant to insult you"...  I would get BLASTED for taking the side of someone attacking her, and would become the new focus of her rage.  She seemed to enjoy doing this with women more often.. I think it was because she could also use the opportunity to accuse me of wanting to cheat on her with that woman.

As an abused man in love, you start to question whether she's right.. whether your "insults" against her really are as bad as she claims, whether you truly deserve the lashing out at you... you apologize for your actions, even though you really have no clue what you have done.  I, like Mr. Depp, would pull away and "vanish" (her word for it) after an altercation.  Sometimes for hours, or even a day or longer.  She openly called me an abuser, a manipulator, and cruel.  In the end, she had me so spun up that I couldn't even tell if what she said was true.. that maybe I really WAS saying things to her that could be considered abusive.

In the end, I realized that she was the abusive one, and ONLY her.  She was masterful at finding angles through which to take offense at something.. literally ANYTHING said, and especially if it was anything resembling a challenge to her perfection.  If she said something that was blatantly factually wrong, and I offered a neutral correction, simply pointing out the factual error.. that was abuse in her mind, and off we'd go on another screaming match, with her accusing me of belittling her, and me claiming I was only trying to offer a correction... and the only way out of it was to accept that I had been rude to her and apologize.

Johnny mentions "jelly in my brain" or something similar in one of the discussions.. about how he had to leave and just sit at work and let his brain de-gel or something to that effect.  I know EXACTLY what he means.  You are basically shell-shocked after one of those tirades, because you absolutely have no idea what the hell you did wrong.. but you love this person.. they can't just be someone with ill-intent, right? So that means there MUST have been something you did, and you just comb through everything in your head and try to figure out what the hell just happened.... and, unfortunately, eventually you key on something and convince yourself that YEAH, I can see how that could have come across how she said.. YEAH, ok, I'll fix that.  BUT IT NEVER WORKS.
